    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1960-01-19T11:40:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1960-01-19T10:00:00-05:00" n="134"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d134">
                <head>134. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d134fn0"
                        >Source: Eisenhower Library, Whitman File, DDE Diaries. Secret; Limit
                        Distribution. Drafted by <persName>Parsons</persName>. See also <ref
                            target="#d132">Documents 132</ref>, <ref target="#d133">133</ref>, and
                            <ref target="#d135">135</ref>–<ref target="#d138">138</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            from="1960-01-19T10:00:00-05:00" to="1960-01-19T11:40:00-05:00"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date">January 19, 1960, 10–11:40
                            a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>The President’s Visit to Japan<note n="1" xml:id="d134fn1">The President’s
                            visit to Japan scheduled for June 20 was announced on January 20. For
                            text of the press release, see Department of State <hi rend="italic"
                                >Bulletin</hi>, February 8, 1960, p. 181.</note>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>[Here follows the same list as <ref target="#d132">Document
                        132</ref>.]</item>
                </list>
                <p>The President informed Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_KN1">Kishi</persName>
                    that he had just learned of Soviet approval for travel arrangements on his
                    forthcoming trip to the Soviet Union. These arrangements will permit him to
                    visit Japan on his return from the Soviet Union. He said that he was delighted
                    to be able to accept the Prime Minister’s previous invitation to visit
                    Japan.</p>
            </div>
